25|$|Benzoic acid was {{discovered}} in the sixteenth century. The dry distillation of <b>gum</b> <b>benzoin</b> was first described by Nostradamus (1556), and then by Alexius Pedemontanus (1560) and Blaise de Vigenère (1596).|$|E
25|$|The first {{industrial}} process involved {{the reaction of}} benzotrichloride (trichloromethyl benzene) with calcium hydroxide in water, using iron or iron salts as catalyst. The resulting calcium benzoate is converted to benzoic acid with hydrochloric acid. The product contains significant amounts of chlorinated benzoic acid derivatives. For this reason, benzoic acid for human consumption was obtained by dry distillation of <b>gum</b> <b>benzoin.</b> Food-grade benzoic acid is now produced synthetically.|$|E
